{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d0f2f98b-4010-453b-a7e5-be595e100ff5","content":"These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes:\n\n---\n\n**1. `left && right` — stricter compile-time checks with `dynamic`**\n\nThe `&&` operator requires both `operator true`/`operator false` **and** `operator &` on the static type. Previously, when one operand was `dynamic`, the compiler deferred *all* resolution to runtime. C# 15 now validates the non-dynamic operand's static type (`IFilter`) at compile time — and `IFilter` doesn't define `operator &`.\n\n**Fixes** (pick one):\n- Add `static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y)` to the interface\n- Cast both sides to `dynamic`: `(dynamic)left && right`\n- Use explicit logic: `IFilter.operator_false(left) ? left : (left & right)`\n\n---\n\n**2. `ref readonly` lambda — CS0518 missing predefined type**\n\nC# 15 now supports `ref readonly` returns on lambdas by synthesizing an anonymous delegate type. That synthesized delegate requires a new well-known attribute/type (to encode the `ref readonly` on the return) that only ships in the **.NET 11 base class libraries**.\n\nIf your project targets an older TFM (e.g., `net8.0`, `net9.0`) but uses the C# 15 compiler via `<LangVersion>15</LangVersion>`, the required type isn't present → CS0518.\n\n**Fix:** Set `<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>` in your `.csproj`, or — if you must multi-target — avoid `ref readonly` lambdas on older TFMs and use a named method with an explicit delegate type instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1b665508-1446-4802-a59c-11f3a1fbff3b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both cases.\n\n**Case 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a known breaking change related to how the compiler handles short-circuiting operators (`&&` / `||`) when one operand is `dynamic`. \n\nThe `&&` operator in C# is a short-circuit operator that relies on `operator true`/`operator false` and `operator &`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler previously would defer the entire resolution to runtime. But in C# 15, the compiler changed behavior around how it resolves these operators with `dynamic` operands.\n\n\nThe compiler is now stricter about resolving short-circuit operators when `dynamic` is involved—it can't simply defer everything to the runtime binder anymore, which is likely why the `&&` operation between `left` and `right` is failing. The `&&` operator relies on `operator false` for short-circuiting and `operator &` for the actual operation, but `IFilter` doesn't define `operator &` — only `CompositeFilter` does. Since `left` is typed as `IFilter` and `right` is `dynamic`, the runtime binder needs to resolve this, which might be where C# 15 introduced a breaking change in how it handles operator resolution with dynamic operands on interface types. C# 15 / Roslyn is related to **user-defined compound assignment and short-circuit operators with `dynamic`**. There was a change where the compiler now performs more compile-time checking even when `dynamic` is involved, rather than deferring everything to runtime.\n\nSpecifically, for `&&` with a `dynamic` operand, the compiler in C# 15 now checks at compile time that the static type of the non-dynamic operand has `operator true`/`operator false` and `operator &`. Previously, this was all deferred to runtime. Since `IFilter` (the static type of `left`) defines `operator true`/`operator false` but NOT `operator &`, the compiler now raises an error.\n\nThe fix would be to add the missing `operator &` to the `IFilter` interface, cast `left` to `dynamic` as well to make both operands dynamic, or use a different approach altogether.\n\nNow looking at the `RefHelper.cs` case with the `ref readonly` lambda. The error CS0518 indicates the compiler is looking for a predefined type that isn't available—likely a new delegate type or attribute that C# 15 requires for `ref readonly` returns from lambdas. This suggests the target framework or runtime doesn't have the necessary support yet. `ref readonly` returns on lambdas require the compiler to synthesize a delegate type that can express this semantic, and in C# 15 this likely depends on a new BCL type or attribute that's missing when targeting older frameworks—the fix would be to target `net11.0` or provide a polyfill for the missing type. Now I'm reconsidering the dynamic && operator issue with interface implementations to give a more accurate explanation. one operand is `dynamic`. Specifically, for `left && right` where `left: IFilter` and `right: dynamic`, the compiler now validates at compile time that the static type (`IFilter`) supports the `&` operator. Since `IFilter` only defines `operator true`/`operator false` but not `operator &`, this fails.\n\nIn previous versions, when `dynamic` was involved, the compiler would emit a dynamic call site that resolved everything at runtime, where it would find `CompositeFilter.operator &` if `left` happened to be a `CompositeFilter` at runtime. C# 15 tightened this.\n\n**Issue 2 - ref readonly lambda:**\n\nThe CS0518 error suggests a well-known type is missing that C# 15 needs for `ref readonly` return lambdas, likely something like `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.ScopedRefAttribute` or a similar marker that encodes the `ref readonly` semantics on synthesized delegate types. This would only be available in newer runtimes, so targeting an older framework with the C# 15 compiler would trigger this error.\n\nThe fix for both issues is to either update the target framework to `net11.0` or later, or adjust the code to avoid these C# 15 features.","outputTokens":2732,"requestId":"D82B:229004:645DEBA:6D90C5B:69F162DC"},"id":"8d971253-2296-4339-971e-c1259c019be1","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:47:03.917Z","parentId":"5eaabd98-a66f-400e-a559-e43d10f64700"}
